Title : Susanne Grinder
Text : '''Susanne Grinder''' (born November 1981) is a Danish  ballet dancer. She joined the [[Royal Danish Ballet]] in 1998, becoming a principal dancer in 2012.

==Early life==
Born in [[Helsingør]] in 1981, her father is a bank manager, her mother a graduate in Danish and history of art. She was brought up in [[Snekkersten]] in the north of [[Zealand]] as the youngest of four children. Like her sister Anne Mie, she went to local ballet classes. Noticing her talent, the teacher recommended she should attend the [[Royal Danish Ballet School]] where she was admitted at the age of seven.<ref name=ss>{{cite web|url=http://www.b.dk/personlig-udvikling/susanne-grinder-den-noedvendige-smerte|title=Susanne Grinder: Den nødvendige smerte|author=Sarah Skarum|publisher=''Berlinske''|date=11 June 2012|accessdate=1 May 2014 |language=Danish}}</ref>

==Career==
After graduating from the ballet school, she became an apprentice at the Royal Danish Ballet in 1998, a member of the corps in 2000, a soloist in 2005 and in 2010 she was promoted to principal dancer after debuting as Odette/Odile in ''[[Swan Lake]]''. Other leading roles include Aurora in ''[[The Sleeping Beauty (ballet)|The Sleeping Beauty]]'', Marguerite in [[John Neumeier|Neumeier]]'s ''[[The Lady of the Camellias|Lady of the Camellias]]'' and Juliet in ''[[Romeo and Juliet (Prokofiev)|Romeo and Juliet]]''. She has also starred in [[August Bournonville]]'s ballets, as Sylphide in ''[[La Sylphide]]'', Teresina in ''[[Napoli (ballet)|Napoli ]]'', Hilda in ''[[A Folk Tale]]'' and Eleonora in ''[[The Kermesse in Bruges]]''. Other highlights have included the title role in ''[[Giselle]]'' and Nikiya in ''[[La Bayadère]]''. She has performed abroad in Spain, Italy, France, Russia, Germany and the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kglteater.dk/about-us/cv/s/susanne-grinder|title=Susanne Grinder|publisher=Det Kongelige Teater|accessdate=1 May 2014 |language=}}</ref>

When she was 26, Grinder contracted a serious illness which proved to be [[Lemierre's syndrome]]. As a result, it was a year before she could return to the stage.<ref name=ss/>

